This is a known pain point. In .NET 10, MAUI enables **edge-to-edge** rendering on Android by default, which makes the old `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` (and the MAUI `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` wrapper) stop working as expected.

## The fix

Use the new **`KeyboardOverlapMode`** platform-specific that was added for .NET 10. In your `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration;
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.AndroidSpecific;

// In CreateMauiApp():
builder
    .UseMauiApp<App>()
    .ConfigureMauiHandlers(handlers =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        Microsoft.Maui.ApplicationModel.Platform.ActivityStateChanged += (_, e) =>
        {
            if (e.State == Android.App.ActivityState.Created)
            {
                // This replaces the old WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize
                e.Activity.Window?.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false);
            }
        };
#endif
    });
```

But the **simplest approach** is to apply it at the page level using the new API:

```xml
<!-- In your page XAML -->
<ContentPage xmlns:android="clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.AndroidSpecific;
             assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls"
             android:Application.WindowSoftInputModeAdjust="Resize">

    <Grid RowDefinitions="*,Auto">
        <!-- Chat messages -->
        <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ... />

        <!-- Input bar — this will move up with the keyboard -->
        <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1">
            <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
            <Button Text="Send" />
        </HorizontalStackLayout>
    </Grid>
</ContentPage>
```

## If that still doesn't work (edge-to-edge conflict)

Override the edge-to-edge behavior in your **AndroidManifest.xml** or your `MainActivity`:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    // Re-enable the classic resize behavior
    Window?.SetSoftInputMode(Android.Views.SoftInput.AdjustResize);

    // Tell the framework the content should fit inside system windows
    AndroidX.Core.View.ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
        Window!.DecorView,
        new KeyboardInsetsListener());
}

private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object,
    AndroidX.Core.View.IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public AndroidX.Core.View.WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(
        Android.Views.View v,
        AndroidX.Core.View.WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(
            AndroidX.Core.View.WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var systemBarInsets = insets.GetInsets(
            AndroidX.Core.View.WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());

        // Apply bottom padding = max(keyboard, nav bar)
        v.SetPadding(
            systemBarInsets.Left,
            systemBarInsets.Top,
            systemBarInsets.Right,
            Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, systemBarInsets.Bottom));

        return insets;
    }
}
```

## TL;DR

| .NET 9 | .NET 10 |
|---|---|
| `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` | Use `WindowInsetsCompat` with IME insets in `MainActivity`, or opt out of edge-to-edge |

The `WindowInsetsCompat` listener approach (last example) is the most reliable — it works with edge-to-edge and gives you explicit control over how the keyboard inset is applied.
